    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey quick question, im managing a clothing boutique and im trying to figure out how to calculate the inventory turnover ratio. also what does it actually mean if my ratio is pretty low? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inventory turnover ratio is simply the number of times your stock is sold and replaced over a specific period, like a year. It's calculated by dividing your total sales by your average inventory. If your ratio is low, it means your shop is holding onto clothes for too long, which is a major red flag for a busy boutique.\n\nA low ratio suggests that your customers aren't buying what you have, or perhaps your pricing is too high, or you're just not selling fast enough. In the world of fashion, this is a disaster because clothes sit in the closet for months, and the more you hold onto them, the more you lose money on storage and the more you risk them going out of style.\n\nYou might think you're just being conservative, but in the world of fashion, being conservative is often a sign of a slow-moving stockroom. If your ratio is low, it means your customers are either not interested in your clothes, or you're not marketing them effectively enough. You need to figure out why your customers aren't buying what you have.\n\nIf your ratio is low, it means your customers are not buying what you have, or perhaps your pricing is too high, or you're just not selling fast enough",
